 ISMARA'S DOOM
A Chronicle of the Parks Group

CHAPTER TWO: THE DEAD BELOW

PART I: SHELOB RETURNS
She came back in the early morning with cheese on her breath and several new bruises and an expression of profound personal satisfaction that suggested the bruises had been worth it.
Shelob the Orc dropped into the back of the cart, accepted the looks she received with the equanimity of someone who does not experience judgment as a meaningful category, and helped herself to what remained of breakfast. She had acquired cheese by methods she did not specify. She had, she mentioned, slept with bears. She said this in the tone of a person reporting weather conditions — factual, complete, not inviting follow-up.
[Wood Elf Name] looked briefly at the middle distance. Y'droj's expression did not change. [Khajiit Name] accepted it the way she had learned to accept most things about Shelob, which was to say she filed it and moved on.
They caught her up. Dar-Ma crystallizing above the apothecary. Bered in the temple, his eyes going strange, repeating the same half-sentence about pain. The collector with the necromantic shelves who had known what the marks meant and had not said how. The court scholar and his discovery of small decorative hearts in a notation system older than his oldest references.
Shelob listened with the attention she gave things she found interesting. She ate the cheese.
Then Hrolf Stone-Fist arrived, and the look on his face said everything before his mouth opened.

PART II: WHAT HAPPENED OVERNIGHT
Four more.
He told them on the road between the cart and the temple, walking fast, not quite looking at them — carrying information that needed to be put somewhere and was heavy to carry alone. Four more overnight. Same marks, same geometry, same luminous blue-white from inside the tissue. One found in the market before dawn. One in the corner of the Candlehearth common room, standing with open eyes, found by a serving girl coming to clean the hearth. Two outside near the Gray Quarter gate, standing at the edge of the cobblestones like they were waiting to cross.
Standing. Alive. Eyes tracking. Not falling, not screaming, positioned at specific points in the city like they had walked there deliberately and then simply stopped.
Y'droj was mapping them. He had begun last night before he slept, and in his notebook the positions were accumulating into a shape he could not yet fully read but could already tell was not random.
At the temple, Bered was worse.
His eyes were fully changed now — the irises gone opaque, the color replaced by something that caught the light like cut glass, beautiful and deeply wrong. His chest rose over the course of ten slow seconds and fell. Helgrid moved around the table and his crystalline eyes tracked her. He was entirely present and entirely unreachable, like a man behind glass in a room you could not find the door to.
Then Helgrid pulled back the sheet on what had been brought in overnight. Found at the base of the Hall of the Dead's exterior steps. This one was different: the marks were present but they had been cut from the outside, not grown from within, and even to eyes that did not know Atmoran notation the difference was visible. The geometry was similar — the same system, recognizably — but the lines were too thick in places, the angles slightly wrong, the spacing inconsistent in the way of someone working from observation rather than understanding. And in several places the marks had burst. The tissue had rejected something introduced too quickly, too crudely, and the rejection had been violent.
[Wood Elf Name] looked at the two sets of marks for a long moment. At Bered's — internal, precise, architectural, coming from within. At the figure's — external, improving, but still wrong in the same fundamental way.
"Two people are doing this," she said.
Not a question. A conclusion arrived at cleanly, the way she arrived at most things.
Y'droj's notebook was already open.

PART III: WHERE ISMARA WAS
They found her in the Hall of the Dead.
Not waiting. Working. She was at the entrance to the lower levels — the old stonework that the Hall had been built over, pre-Nordic construction that sat beneath the building like a different era of the world expressing itself through the foundation — and she was moving her hand along the wall with the focused attention of someone reading. Her finger traced a line in the fitted stone and stopped. She made a note in her notebook without looking at the page. She moved three feet to the left and began again.
She had been here for some time. She turned when they arrived with the unhurried acknowledgment of someone who had registered their approach earlier and chosen to continue working through it.
She looked at [Khajiit Name]. She wrote:
You are here. Good.
A second line:
Take me down.

PART IV: THE NOTE
Before they descended she wrote something longer.
Not the notation she used for her own records — that was for walls, for architecture, for the private language she worked in. This was in Common, careful and deliberate, in a handwriting that Wulfgar had described as archaic, overly formal, consistent with someone who has been writing this language for a very long time. She filled most of a page. She tore it out. She handed it to [Khajiit Name].
[Khajiit Name] read it. Her expression did not give much away. She passed it to Y'droj.
Y'droj and [Wood Elf Name] spent twenty minutes on it together.
Atmoran Common was not exactly Common. It was Common the way a very old river is still water — recognizably the same substance but moving according to principles laid down before the current world knew it needed them. The vocabulary had roots in modern language but the roots were deep and the grammar had grown in directions that required inference, cross-reference, and the willingness to be wrong several times before being right.
They had been learning since the night before, since Wulfgar's study, since they had sat with his transcriptions and worked backwards from what they knew. They were not fluent. They were beginning.
The note, assembled piece by piece in the margin of Y'droj's notebook, said: the catacombs below this hall are old. The architecture will be familiar to her and disorienting to them. There are defenses — not Draugr, not traps, but perceptual mechanisms that will interfere with their sense of direction and spatial reasoning. These can be navigated. Move between the pulses.
Then one more line at the bottom, the simplest and therefore the most compressed:
Trust the path that does not feel like a path.
Y'droj and [Wood Elf Name] looked at each other.
"Right," [Wood Elf Name] said.
They went down.

PART V: SHELOB'S METHODOLOGY
The first chamber was cold in the way that old things are cold — not aggressive winter cold or the ambient cold that followed Ismara, but the deep settled cold of stone that had not been warm in centuries and had stopped expecting warmth.
It was occupied.
Two Draugr stood in the far corner by shattered alcoves — ancient, desiccated, armor rusted to abstract shapes, blue fire in their eye sockets. They turned toward the group's torchlight with the slow inevitability of things built for a purpose they had been waiting to execute.
Y'droj assessed. Cover behind the broken alcoves. Two opponents, slow, not bothered by cold. The boot prints in the dust cut straight through without pausing — someone who walked these halls regularly and was not concerned about what lived here.
Shelob assessed differently.
She began to dance.
Dance was, technically, the correct word, in the way that damp is technically the correct word for the inside of a waterfall. It was a performance of such absolute commitment, such physical totality, such complete and apparently sincere conviction that she was the most interesting thing in this chamber, that both Draugr stopped.
They stared.
Something in their ancient programming encountered Shelob's methodology and experienced a category error. They had been built for threat detection. They could not look away. The rest of the party moved around the edges of the chamber quickly and quietly while Shelob held the center, and they passed through the far gate into the corridor beyond while the Draugr remained in the grip of an attention they could not exit.
Shelob acknowledged her performance by doing it again, more thoroughly, establishing certain facts about herself and the architecture of the encounter in a manner that was comprehensive and seemingly educational for all parties involved.
She contracted the rotjoint somewhere in this process.
She joined the party in the corridor with the expression of someone who has completed a task to her own satisfaction. She was limping very slightly. She did not mention the rotjoint. Y'droj noted the limp and filed it.
They chose the left door — two options — and picked correctly on the first attempt.

PART VI: THE MAZE
The maze was not a maze in the physical sense. The corridors were fixed. The stone was where it had always been. The people who had built this place had understood that the most durable defenses were not walls but confusion — the targeting of spatial reasoning, which most people used constantly and never thought about until it failed them.
The wards hit in waves. A vertigo that arrived from no direction. A flickering wrongness at the edge of vision. And then the certain knowledge that the corridor ahead was not the one they had been in a moment ago — not different, not moved, simply unfamiliar in the way a known room becomes unfamiliar when entered from an unexpected angle in the dark.
Y'droj went first, because method was the answer to disorientation, and method began with going and observing and coming back. He went into the first room and catalogued it. Into the second. Into the fifth — which was not the fifth in any sequential sense but was what the maze's geometry eventually produced if you followed it with sufficient patience — and in the fifth room he found the door to Calixto's workshop.
He turned back to the problem of communication.
In here, go north meant nothing. Directions were advisory at best and actively misleading at worst. He reached for the channel Ismara had established — the alteration working she had laid across them that allowed something like thought to pass between them without going through sound. He used it the way a surveyor uses language: not directions but orientations. Not go north but the door you want faces the same direction as the door you came through but will feel like it faces away from you. Relationships between spaces rather than absolute positions. The shape of the path rather than its compass heading.
[Wood Elf Name] received it. Adjusted it. Passed it back with her own spatial reasoning added. The conversation was not in words — it was in geometry, in the logic of how spaces related to each other, in a language that the maze could not scramble because it was not made of directions.
One by one, they came through.
Ismara had come through first. She was examining the workshop walls when they arrived, her finger on the stone, reading whatever the stone said to her.

PART VII: THE MUSEUM MAN'S WORKSHOP
It smelled like embalming fluid and ambition and the chemical sweetness of alchemical processes running for weeks without adequate ventilation.
The worktables were covered in Calixto's work — not just equipment, but the evidence of a progression. Vellum sheets pinned in chronological order along the far wall. Early sheets: large imprecise notation, the Atmoran system copied by someone who had studied it without learning it, with annotations in his handwriting filling the margins — wrong, wrong, why wrong. Later sheets: finer, smaller, more careful. The most recent sheet: almost clean. Almost.
Two alcoves modified into cells. One empty, with dark stains on the stone. One occupied.
The woman — Viola, she said eventually, after [Wood Elf Name] had cast the calm spell and it had settled over her like weather changing — pressed herself against the far wall when the cell opened, because she had been here long enough to learn what the door opening meant. When she understood they were not Calixto, she stopped pressing.
"The museum man." Her voice was rough from the gag. "He did this. He runs a — there's a museum, on the main street. He calls it a House of Curiosities."
They looked at the stone slab in the center of the room. At the assembled figure on it — stitched, augmented, covered in dense carved notation that was recognizably the same system as the marks on Bered's arm in the way that a very good forgery is recognizable when placed beside the original. Similar shapes. Wrong logic. The tissue around the carved marks had responded violently to several of them. Calixto's finest work. Still not right.
Ismara looked at the slab. She picked up one of the vellum sheets from the worktable and held it the way a reader holds a page in a language they know well enough to hear every wrong note. She set it down.
She wrote one line:
He is copying. Poorly.
She moved to the slab. She examined the figure briefly. She started writing something else — her pen moved across the page for several words — and then she stopped. She crossed out what she had written with a single precise line. She wrote instead:
It would not have worked.
[Khajiit Name] was close enough to see the crossed-out text. Close enough to see that there had been more, before the line. She could not read what was underneath it. The crossing-out was thorough.
Ismara put her notebook away.
Calixto's journal was on the worktable, open. Y'droj read it in chronological order — the weeks of frustration, the incremental refinement, the escalating certainty, the final entry written in handwriting that had lost some of its precision:
Visitors today. They had marks — the real marks, not mine. The Khajiit especially. The notation on her is fluent. Accent marks I have never seen. Someone who actually understands this system is working in this city and I do not know who they are. The resonance from outside is stronger than ever. I must accelerate.
Y'droj read this passage twice.
He looked up from the journal.
Ismara was reading the far wall.
He looked at [Khajiit Name].
[Khajiit Name] was reading the journal entry over his shoulder. Several things were happening in her expression simultaneously and she had not yet decided which one to show.
Nobody said anything.
They helped Viola to her feet. They found the necromancer's amulet in a worktable drawer. They gathered what they could. Then they navigated back through the maze by the geometry they had mapped — Y'droj and [Wood Elf Name] working through the sequence of rooms together, checking each junction against the shape of the path they had built between them — until they reached room eight.
The fissure in the wall appeared to be a hole in the fabric of the room.
Y'droj had encountered illusion magic before. He knew what it was and what it was designed to do — to redirect attention, to make the path forward seem like something that should not be approached. He knew this. He also knew that the part of his mind responsible for spatial reasoning was looking at the fissure and producing a strong and specific recommendation to go somewhere else immediately.
He looked at Ismara.
She looked at the fissure. The way she looked at things — complete, assessing, filing. Then she walked through it.
On the other side, they heard Calixto's voice.

PART VIII: THE END OF THE ROPE
The fissure opened into the largest chamber yet — ceiling arching into darkness above pillars carved as warriors, iron braziers at the corners bleeding orange light across old stone. The cold here was of a different quality than the cold above: the deep cold of something that had been waiting for a very long time.
Calixto was at the far end.
His fine clothes had not survived the weeks underground — stained at the hem, the embroidered cuffs gone dark. He was hunched over an altar of bone with the total focus of a man who had crossed the threshold between obsession and somewhere further along that road, somewhere without a comfortable name. His hands were moving. He was carving.
Behind him, near a cracked sarcophagus: nine feet of ancient ceremonial plate crusted with ice that had been growing for a very long time. A greatsword of black iron. Blue fire in eye sockets that had not closed in four thousand years. The Draugr Crypt Guardian — and around Calixto's neck, a bone-and-wire amulet pulsing with the desperate energy of a man holding open a door that wanted badly to close.
The same construction as the amulets on his shop shelves. The same logic. Less decorative. More load-bearing.
Calixto heard them. He turned.
The man who had been warm and curious and delighted to meet the heroes of Frostmere was gone in the way that personas go when the performance cost exceeds what the performer can sustain. What was left was the research. The methodology. The certainty that he was close — always close — that the next subject would be the one where it worked, and that everything he had done in service of this was justified by what the working was for.
"You don't understand," he said. The words had the smooth quality of a sentence repeated until the edges wore off. "I'm so close. The Atmorans preserved consciousness for millennia — I've cracked their method. One more subject. Everything I've done — it's been for this. To bring her back."
He was not talking to them. He was in the place where the methodology lived, where the weeks of vellum sheets and refined notation and the incremental progress from wrong to almost had become the only country with solid ground in it.
Behind him, the Guardian's blue fire eyes did not move from the back of his head.
The amulet pulsed.
Y'droj looked at the unlit braziers at each corner. At the pillars — cover, full cover, if the Guardian's reach was what he estimated. At Viola, standing at his shoulder, who had been in this room before as a subject and was in it again on different terms. At Calixto, still explaining himself to people who had stopped being the audience for this particular argument somewhere around the word understand.
He looked at the Guardian and the amulet connecting it to the man in front of it.
He looked at Calixto — the fever in his eyes, the conviction, the to bring her back with no named referent, the workshop full of attempts that had killed people and been filed and refined and attempted again with greater precision. The vellum sheets. The escalating neatness of a man learning a language by practicing it on people who could not consent to the lesson.
And Y'droj thought, standing in the cold of the final chamber with Calixto's voice filling the space: he found the marks on [Khajiit Name] and recognized them as fluent. He called them the real marks. He has been trying to replicate something that already exists, that is already in motion, that is better at this than he is and has been doing it longer.
He is not the source. He is the imitation.
He did not say this aloud. There was a fight first.
He looked at the braziers. He looked at [Wood Elf Name]. He looked at Shelob, who had acquired the expression of someone who has been waiting patiently for the part of the evening she was actually suited for.
Calixto was still talking.
The amulet pulsed.

Outside, in the dark above the city, Bjorn smoked his pipe on the bench of the cart. Mable stood patient in her traces. The cart sat quiet on the road with the frost on its canvas and the cold inside it that was not quite winter cold and not quite anything else.
In his notebook, closed on his chest upstairs in the night before all of this, Y'droj had written: she knows where she is going.
He had not known, then, what that meant.
He was beginning to.


